<div id='tutoMOD_1' class='modal' style="display: block;">
  <div class='modalcontent_TUTO'>
    <h5>Welcome to the tutorial of RECIFS</h5>
    <br>
    <p class='tutoTXT'>RECIFS is the acronym for "Reef Environment Centralized InFormation System". <br>
      <br>
      RECIFS is an online application allowing the user to explore environmental variation across any reef system around the world. 
      The environmental data shown in RECIFS comes from several public databases, and can be visualized and dowloaded in complete open access. 
      <br><br>
      In this tutorial, you will learn how to use the different functionalities of RECIFS. 
      <br><br>
      Follow the instructions written in the green dialog boxes. If you  need to reread the instructions or move to the next step of the tutorial, click on the tutorial button (<img style="width: 0.8cm; background-color: #3c680a;" src="public/buttons/buttonT.svg">) in the bottom-right corner of the interface.
    </p>
    <br>
    <button onclick='transitionTUTO1()'>Let's start!</button>
  </div>
</div>


<div id='tutoMOD_2' class='modal' style="display: none;">
  <div class='modalcontent_TUTO'>
    <h5>1. Select study area</h5>
    <br>
    <p class='tutoTXT'>The first step when using RECIFS is selecting an area of interest. <br>
      <br>
      Any region of the world having coral reefs can be selected as study area.  
      <br><br>
      There are no particular restriction in size, but bear in mind that if you select very large areas the computations of RECIFS will be slower. 
      <br><br>
      In this tutorial, you will work on the reefs of the Red Sea. Move through the map to the Red Sea (highlighted by a green polygon). 
      Then click on the "Area of Interest" button in the top panel, and draw the Area of Interest around the Red Sea.
    </p>
    <br>
    <button onclick='transitionTUTO2()'>OK</button>
  </div>
</div>



<div id='tutoMOD_3' class='modal' style="display: none;">
  <div class='modalcontent_TUTO'>
    <h5>2. Visualize environmental variation</h5>
    <br>
    <p class='tutoTXT'>You will see that the reefs of the Red Sea are now shown on the map. <br>
      <br>
      By default, RECIFS displays the average level of Sea Surface Temperature over the past decades.   
      <br><br>
      You can visualize other environmental variables by clicking on the "Environment" button. 
      This will open a panel with a set of environmental variables that are pre-computed by RECIFS. 
    </p>
    <br>
    <button onclick='transitionTUTO3()'>OK</button>
  </div>
</div>



<div id='tutoMOD_4' class='modal' style="display: none;">
  <div class='modalcontent_TUTO'>
    <h5>2. Visualize environmental variation</h5>
    <br>
    <p class='tutoTXT'>
      For some variables, you can either display the overall average (<button style="background-color: #0f497e;">MEA</button>) or the overall standard deviation (<button style="background-color: #0f497e;">STD</button>). 
      For other variables, you can visualize the values computed on a radius or 10 (<button style="background-color: #0f497e;">10k</button>) or 50 (<button style="background-color: #0f497e;">50k</button>) km. 
      <br><br>
      If you want to find out more precisely how each variable was computed, and what are the original data sources, click on the <button class='ENVinfoB'>i</button> button next to the variable of interest. 
      <br><br>
      Try to visualize different types of variables, and use the information button to display the data sources. 
      When you are done, click on the on the tutorial button (<img style="width: 0.8cm; background-color: #3c680a;" src="public/buttons/buttonT.svg">) to continue. 
    </p>
    <br>
    <button onclick='transitionTUTO4()'>OK</button>
  </div>
</div>



<div id='tutoMOD_5' class='modal' style="display: none;">
  <div class='modalcontent_TUTO'>
    <h5>3. Advanced environmetal characterization </h5>
    <br>
    <p class='tutoTXT'>
      In RECIFS it is possible to customize the computation of environmental variables using the "advanced mode".  
      <br><br>
      For example, in the "advanced mode" you can compute environmental characterization for a specific time window, or using a specific statistcal measure (e.g. mean, standard deviation, median, minimal, maximal).
      <br><br>
      To activate the "advanced mode", click on the <button style="background-color: #0f497e;">ADVANCED</button> button, in the environmental panel. 
       </p>
    <br>
    <button onclick='transitionTUTO5()'>OK</button>
  </div>
</div>


<div id='tutoMOD_6' class='modal' style="display: none;">
  <div class='modalcontent_TUTO'>
    <h5>3. Advanced environmnetal characterization </h5>
    <br>
    <p class='tutoTXT'>
      You can use this interface to customize the environmnetal characterization. 
      <br><br>
      For variables having multiple measures over time (e.g. Sea surface temperature), you can restrict the computations to specific temporal windows. 
      For example, you can compute the characterization of a given variable across a specifc range of years, and/or only for specific months. 
      You can also decide which statistic to compute (e.g. mean, standard deviation, median, minimal, maximal).
      <br><br>
      For variables without measures over time (e.g. landcover-derived variables such as density of build-up area), you can decide the size of the radius over which the variable is calculated. 
      <br><br>
      The interface also allows you to customize the limits and the colors used in the colorscale displayed on the map. 
      <br><br>
      In this tutorial, we will focus on <b>standard deviation</b> of <b>sea surface temperature</b> over the decade between <b>2010 and 2020</b>. <br>
      Use the inferface to adjust the settings, then click on the <button style="background-color: #0f497e;">RUN</button> button to perform the computations in "advanced mode"-
      <br><br>
      When you are done, click on the on the tutorial button (<img style="width: 0.8cm; background-color: #3c680a;" src="public/buttons/buttonT.svg">) to continue. 
    </p>
    <br>
    <button onclick='transitionTUTO6()'>OK</button>
  </div>
</div>


<div id='tutoMOD_7' class='modal' style="display: none;">
